diff --git a/docs/appendices/release-notes/5.7.3.rst b/docs/appendices/release-notes/5.7.3.rst
index 7add06fd16..fcba0f1e33 100644
--- a/docs/appendices/release-notes/5.7.3.rst
+++ b/docs/appendices/release-notes/5.7.3.rst
@@ -48,4 +48,9 @@ See the :ref:`version_5.7.0` release notes for a full list of changes in the
 Fixes
 =====

-None
+- Fixed an issue that prevented sub-columns of a view to be shown in the
+  ``information_schema.columns`` table if only top-level columns were used in
+  the view's SELECT query. Workaround: explicitly select sub-columns in the
+  view definition, e.g.::
+
+      CREATE VIEW v AS SELECT a, a['b'] FROM t;
diff --git a/docs/sql/statements/create-view.rst b/docs/sql/statements/create-view.rst
index 3f2175a35c..c2ad34a199 100644
--- a/docs/sql/statements/create-view.rst
+++ b/docs/sql/statements/create-view.rst
@@ -61,6 +61,14 @@ operations.
   been created, these columns will show up in subsequent queries on the view.
   It is generally recommended to avoid using ``*`` in view definitions.

+ .. NOTE::
+
+   If an object column is selected, sub-columns are visible in the
+   ``information_schema.columns`` table. Added sub-columns at the source
+   relation are visible there while dropped columns won't show up there anymore
+   as well. This applies both to views where ``*`` is used to select columns
+   and to views with a static selection of top level columns.
+

 Privileges
 ==========
